To evaluate predictive factors for pneumonia development, demographics, underlying diseases, and clinical variables of patients in group 2 and 3 were compared to those of patients in group 1 (Table 1, Table 2
). Identified predictive factors are summarized in Table 3
with odd ratios (OR). Increasing age was significantly associated with pneumonia development as a continuous variable (P = 0.015), and age older than 45 years was a predictive factor for the development of pneumonia (OR, 8.04; 95% CI, 1.52–42.43; P = 0.007). Although proportion of male also increased with progression of pneumonia (38.5%, 57.9%, and 84.6% for group 1, 2, and 3, respectively), statistically significant association between male sex and the pneumonia development was not identified (P = 0.097).
